<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF FOREIGN STUDENTS STUDYING IN TAIWAN SOARS 23 PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Feb.  4 (CNA) 02/04/07  16:33:52 (By Deborah Kuo)
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign students seeking education in Taiwan soared
by 23 percent to 14,479 in 2006, mainly as a result of a global
new fad for learning Mandarin, the Ministry of Education reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2006 foreign students, a total of 9,135 were in Taiwan to
study Mandarin at various language centers around the island,
marking an increase of 953 over the year-earlier level, ministry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese dominated  the ranks of Mandarin-learning  foreign
students, with a total of 1,807 students, followed by Indonesians
with 1,279, Americans with 1,252, Koreans with 1,039 and
Vietnamese with 402, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another 3,935 foreign students were in Taiwan last
year studying for academic accreditation, an increase of 1,082
students over the level of a year- earlier, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of these students were from Asian countries and
most of these sought higher education  in fields of science,
engineering, medical and agriculture, they added.
</P>
<P>
Besides Mandarin-learning students and students studying for
academic accreditation, there were 1,409 other foreign students
in Taiwan last year receiving education as "exchange students, "
they noted.
</P>
<P>
Of this group,  245 students went to Taipei's Ming Chuan
University, the top- drawing institution among the 50 Taiwanese
colleges and universities hosting foreign exchange students.
</P>
<P>
Japanese students were again tops in this category, with 265
students on exchange, following by Americans, 204, and Koreans,
186, the officials added.
</P>
